explanation.principle:
When a projectile is launched and lands at the same horizontal level, its horizontal range is the total horizontal distance travelled before it returns to the ground.

The range depends on three factors:

• the launch speed;
• the angle of projection; and
• the acceleration due to gravity.

The range is calculated using

R = (u² sin2θ)/g

where:

• R = horizontal range;
• u = launch speed;
• θ = angle of projection;
• g = acceleration due to gravity.

Notice that the formula uses sin2θ, not sinθ.

A projectile is an object launched into the air and allowed to move under the influence of gravity alone.

The maximum height is the greatest vertical distance reached before the projectile begins to descend.

At this highest point:

• the vertical component of velocity becomes zero;
• the horizontal component of velocity remains constant.

For a projectile that lands at the same level from which it was projected, the maximum height is given by:

H = (u² sin²θ)/(2g)

where:

• H = maximum height;
• u = launch speed;
• θ = angle of projection;
• g = acceleration due to gravity.

When H and u are known, the formula can be rearranged to determine the launch angle.
